Topic: Knowledge check

link: https://www.theodinproject.com/lessons/foundations-introduction-to-git

Objective: Answer questions to check your understanding of this lesson on your own.

1- What kind of program is Git?
Answer:
Is a Distributive Version Control System that keeps a copy of the project in every computer that works on it, so everyone can keep working even if the server goes down.

2-What are the differences between Git and a text editor in terms of what they save and their record keeping?
Git is more organize and no error prone, the information if commited is difficult to lose.

We can check what was changed and by who and revert changes with not much problems.

For backup of the data, git keep a clone in every computer that works in the project and have github for online storage of the project so is pretty difficult to lose a file.

5- Does Git work at a local or remote level?
Works locally and then pull or push commints when it have connection to the internet, so the work wont be stopped.

6- Does GitHub work at a local or remote level?
Is a online service, so is on remote level, and it can keep all the commits in one place when the team members have the time to send commits to it.

7- Why is Git useful for developers?
Several reasons:
Secure
Fast
Flexible
Better commit history

8- Why are Git and GitHub useful for a team of developers?

Since Git is more local, github allows teams to work together in one place, offering the advantages of a central versioning control server, but without the downsides. Plus a lot of other options that offer a better experience for teams to work with.